---HEADER---
file:                  tooling/rules.py
language:              python
role:                  Subcommand validate-rules. Extracts the
                       architectural-rules block from connections.llmainland
                       and groups entries by self-checkable: true | false.
                       The tool itself does NOT validate code; it formats
                       the rules so an LLM can verify a diff against them
                       in one read. With --diff, includes the diff and an
                       LLM instruction in the Report summary.
layer:                 io
status:                verified
confidence:            high (rationale: authored fresh in rc7. Smoke-
                       tested found and fixed a real bug — initial
                       regex matched both "self-checkable: true" and
                       "self-checkable: false" as self-checkable. Fixed.)
generation-pass:       false
read-reason:           task-driven
last-verified:         v0.3-rc7-2026-05-05
maintained-by:         llm
exports:
  - cmd_validate_rules
  - setup_validate_rules
  - SUBCOMMANDS
imports:
  - argparse
  - re
  - pathlib                   :: Path
  - tooling.common            :: MAINLAND_NAME, find_project_root
  - tooling.types             :: Finding, Report
depends-on:
  - llmisland_tooling.py      :: orchestrator iterates SUBCOMMANDS
  - connections.llmainland    :: source document for rule extraction
translation-boundary:  none
dynamic-boundary:      false

---SYMBOLS---

SYMBOL: cmd_validate_rules
kind:           function
pure:           false (filesystem read)
total:          true
latency-budget: <100ms
effects:
  reads:    filesystem (mainland + optional diff)
  mutates:  none
  allocs:   list of Finding objects + summary dict
  throws:   never
  async:    false
  io:       filesystem read
called-by:
  - llmisland_tooling.main :: dispatch on 'validate-rules'
calls:
  - find_project_root, Path.read_text, _extract_rules
expects:
  - args.mainland is None or a path to an existing file
  - args.diff is None or a path to an existing file
runtime-dependencies:
  - none
tests:
  unit:       none yet
  regression: rc7 smoke test: against tooling mainland, correctly
              classified AR-001..AR-004 as self-checkable and AR-005
              as not self-checkable
  security:   none
business-rule: N/A
fragility:    medium (rationale: regex-based extraction is fragile to
                                  format changes in the mainland's
                                  architectural-rules block)
fragility-note: rc7 already caught one regex bug (matching "false" as
                self-checkable). The _extract_rules function below has
                its own SYMBOL entry tracking that fragility.

SYMBOL: setup_validate_rules
kind:           function
pure:           true (mutates parser passed in)
total:          true
latency-budget: <1ms
effects:
  reads:    none
  mutates:  argparse.ArgumentParser
  allocs:   none meaningful
  throws:   never
  async:    false
  io:       none
called-by:
  - llmisland_tooling.build_parser
calls:
  - parser.add_argument
expects:
  - parser supports add_argument
runtime-dependencies:
  - none
tests:
  unit:       none yet
  regression: none yet
  security:   none
business-rule: N/A
fragility:    low
fragility-note: N/A

SYMBOL: SUBCOMMANDS
kind:           constant
pure:           true
total:          true
latency-budget: N/A
effects:
  reads:    none
  mutates:  none
  allocs:   one dict at import time
  throws:   never
  async:    false
  io:       none
called-by:
  - llmisland_tooling.build_parser :: iterates module.SUBCOMMANDS
calls:
  - none
expects:
  - {'validate-rules': (setup_validate_rules, cmd_validate_rules, helptext)}
runtime-dependencies:
  - none
tests:
  unit:       none yet
  regression: none yet
  security:   none
business-rule: N/A
fragility:    low
fragility-note: N/A

---RISKS---

security:                none
regression-sensitivity:
  - any change to the architectural-rules block format in the mainland
    cascades here; the regex must be updated in lockstep
  - the multi-line rule format (continuation indented under AR-NNN:)
    is parsed by taking only the first line; rules that put critical
    information on continuation lines may lose it in the output
platform-sensitivity:
  - none
config-dependencies: none

---MEMORY---

ACTIVE-CONSTRAINTS:
  - id: AC-001
    constraint:  validate-rules MUST distinguish self-checkable: true
                 from self-checkable: false. Treating both as
                 self-checkable surfaces rules that a future LLM
                 cannot verify and produces false confidence.
    established: 2026-05-05
    evidence:    rc7 smoke test caught and fixed this exact bug;
                 see HD-001

  - id: AC-002
    constraint:  the tool is FORMATTING, not validating. The output
                 is for an LLM (or human) to act on; the tool itself
                 cannot verify whether code complies with a rule.
                 Do not add automated verification logic here that
                 pretends to do what RULE 9 in MAINTENANCE PROTOCOL
                 expects from the LLM.
    established: 2026-05-05
    evidence:    inferred-from-spec (SPEC/09_MAINTENANCE.md RULE 9)

HISTORICAL-DECISIONS:
  - id: HD-001
    decision:  bool(re.search) was the original is_self check; fixed
               to compare match.group(1).lower() == "true"
    reason:    bool(re.search(r"self-checkable: (true|false)", ...))
               returns True for ANY match, including "false". The bug
               surfaced in rc7 smoke test against the tooling mainland
               which has self-checkable: false on AR-005 — that rule
               showed up as self-checkable until the fix.
    date:      2026-05-05
    outcome:   fixed in the same RC; first-line is now correctly
               classified by reading the captured group
    evidence:  inferred-from-smoke-test

  - id: HD-002
    decision:  --diff appends the diff to the Report summary, does
               not invoke any external diff tool
    reason:    zero-dependency contract. The user (or an LLM agent)
               passes a pre-computed diff path; this tool does not
               try to run git or compute diffs itself. Keeps the
               surface small and the contract honest.
    date:      2026-05-05
    outcome:   stable
    evidence:  inferred-from-design (zero-dependency contract)

  - id: HD-003
    decision:  output is INFO-level findings, not warnings/errors
    reason:    extraction is informational. ok=True regardless of
               whether rules exist; the LLM consuming the output
               decides what to do with it. An empty rule block
               produces a single warning ("no-rules") because that's
               an actionable signal, but the per-rule entries are
               INFO so they don't pollute exit-code semantics.
    date:      2026-05-05
    outcome:   stable
    evidence:  inferred-from-design

SUPERSEDED:
  - none yet
